li.p:
 To convert from RGB to YC_bC_r, we
	  multiply by P_{\bcal}^{-1} so that




	      \threevec{Y}{C_b}{C_r} =
	      \threevec{76.2}{-43.0}{127.5}




	      \threevec{Y}{C_b}{C_r} =
	      \threevec{29.1}{127.5}{-20.7}




	      \threevec{Y}{C_b}{C_r} =
	      \threevec{255}{0}{0}




	      \threevec{Y}{C_b}{C_r} =
	      \threevec{0}{0}{0}

 To convert from YC_bC_r to RGB, we
	  multiply by P_{\bcal} so that




	      \threevec{R}{G}{B} = \threevec{128}{128}{128}




	      \threevec{R}{G}{B} = \threevec{128}{107.4}{234.3}




	      \threevec{R}{G}{B} = \threevec{212.1}{85.1}{128}

 We have

	    \begin{alignedat}{4}
	    Y \amp {}={} \amp 0.299R \amp {}+{} \amp 0.587G \amp {}+{}
	    \amp 0.114B \\
	    C_b \amp {}={} \amp -0.169R \amp {}-{} \amp 0.331G \amp {}+{}
	    \amp 0.500B \\
	    C_r \amp {}={} \amp 0.500R \amp {}-{} \amp 0.419G \amp {}-{}
	    \amp 0.081B\text{.} \\
	    \end{alignedat}

	  The expression for Y is a weighted average of the
	  R, G, and B values.  The expression for
	  C_b takes half the amount of B and subtracts
	  the amounts of red and green.  Likewise, the expression for
	  C_r takes half the amount of R and subtracts
	  the amounts of green and blue.

We find that
\cfourvec{F_0}{F_1}{\vdots}{F_7} = \left[\begin{array}{c} 151.6\\ 20.01\\ 15.33\\ -6.043\\ -3.712\\ -3.121\\ -0.4167\\ 0.6794\end{array}\right]\text{.}
Notice that the largest Fourier coefficient is F_0=151.6 and that the coefficients F_4, F_5, F_6, and F_7 are relatively small. This reflects the fact that the luminance does not vary rapidly.
